02:03.768 --> 02:06.021
Now, remember,

02:06.536 --> 02:08.437
only 7% of our communication

02:08.479 --> 02:10.801
is based on what we actually say.

02:11.674 --> 02:13.778
38% of it comes from
the tone of the voice,

02:13.810 --> 02:18.545
and the rest of it, 55%,
comes from body language.

02:22.786 --> 02:25.272
Look at the smiles.

02:25.623 --> 02:27.723
Real smiles... they affect the eyes.

02:27.748 --> 02:29.450
They wrinkle the skin.

02:29.527 --> 02:31.973
Is the person making eye contact?

02:32.219 --> 02:33.821
Too much? Not enough?

02:33.884 --> 02:35.786
Oh...

02:37.767 --> 02:40.604
Also pay attention to the direction.

02:40.637 --> 02:41.905
Eyes to the left means that

02:41.939 --> 02:43.107
they're trying to remember something.

02:43.140 --> 02:44.616
Eyes to the right

02:44.674 --> 02:46.788
signals creative thinking,

02:46.844 --> 02:48.412
deception.

02:48.515 --> 02:50.359
Stop.

02:50.447 --> 02:52.984
Devon is the killer.

02:53.049 --> 02:54.618
How'd you figure it out?

02:54.652 --> 02:55.952
Everyone else was, like, really intense

02:55.986 --> 02:57.088
with their eye contact,

02:57.120 --> 02:58.494
and Devon looked away immediately,

02:58.557 --> 03:00.090
like she had something to hide.

03:00.124 --> 03:01.908
That's very good.

03:01.971 --> 03:04.796
Now, remember, this is more
than just a game, right?

03:04.835 --> 03:07.005
I mean, these are skills
that you can use

03:07.030 --> 03:08.131
on a job interview,

03:08.165 --> 03:10.978
on a date, or in bed.

03:12.837 --> 03:15.506
It's a whole new way
of seeing the world,

03:15.539 --> 03:19.076
but you have to look up.

03:24.714 --> 03:27.617
And class is dismissed.

03:27.650 --> 03:29.019
All right, good work, everybody.

03:29.053 --> 03:31.189
We'll see you on Wednesday.

03:34.225 --> 03:35.593
Charlie,

03:35.625 --> 03:37.594
what are you doing here?

03:37.628 --> 03:39.564
Buy you dinner?

03:39.596 --> 03:42.533
How does one teach
interpersonal dynamics?

03:42.565 --> 03:44.077
You saw it. We play "killer,"

03:44.124 --> 03:45.210
we play "red light, green light,"

03:45.265 --> 03:47.771
games that develop observational skills.

03:47.804 --> 03:49.673
And their parents pay money for this?

03:49.707 --> 03:51.608
Well, if their parents knew
how badly they needed it,

03:51.642 --> 03:52.971
- they'd pay twice as much.
- Here you go.

03:52.996 --> 03:54.043
Why do you say that?

03:54.068 --> 03:55.112
- Thank you.
- Sure.

03:55.144 --> 03:56.137
Do you know how much time

03:56.176 --> 03:58.082
the average teen spends
on their devices in one day?

03:58.114 --> 03:59.816
- How much?
- Nine hours,

03:59.850 --> 04:02.753
and in some cases, up to 16 or more.

04:02.785 --> 04:04.120
And in exchange for that,

04:04.154 --> 04:06.023
they get the whole world
in their pocket, right?

04:06.055 --> 04:09.226
Any information, any tool,
right there on their phone.

04:09.268 --> 04:10.970
Is that such a bad thing?

04:10.994 --> 04:12.863
It is if they're not developing

04:12.897 --> 04:14.308
the most important tool of all.

04:14.333 --> 04:15.867
Which is?

04:15.900 --> 04:17.101
Empathy.

04:17.134 --> 04:19.101
We learn empathy by observing,

04:19.136 --> 04:20.237
and we've stopped doing that.

04:20.271 --> 04:22.726
I mean, look.

04:22.939 --> 04:25.942
Nobody's even having
an actual conversation.

04:25.975 --> 04:27.978
- Well, we are.
- Yeah, but that's because

04:28.011 --> 04:29.413
we haven't seen each other
in a few years,

04:29.455 --> 04:32.264
and we have a lot to catch up on.

04:32.749 --> 04:34.584
Want to offer you a job, Mara.

04:36.186 --> 04:37.989
Okay, doing what?

04:38.021 --> 04:40.524
What you did for me on the force:

04:40.588 --> 04:42.790
hostage negotiation.

04:47.230 --> 04:49.369
When I retired as police chief,

04:49.439 --> 04:51.067
I started my private security firm.

04:51.100 --> 04:53.490
Onira-Tech was my first and only client,

04:53.623 --> 04:56.584
and then after a time,
I became a liaison.

05:02.146 --> 05:04.015
"Reverie." What does it do?

05:04.047 --> 05:06.716
What's your all-time favorite memory?

05:06.757 --> 05:08.661
The most beautiful, mind-blowing place

05:08.686 --> 05:10.939
you can remember?

05:13.178 --> 05:15.948
Uh, when I was, um, ten...

05:17.761 --> 05:20.804
My mother took me and my sister Jamie

05:21.331 --> 05:23.166
to this place called
"labyrinth of light."

05:23.241 --> 05:26.218
It was this

05:26.369 --> 05:29.172
field just full of paper lanterns.

05:30.874 --> 05:34.562
It was like floating in space.

05:34.677 --> 05:36.247
What if you could revisit that moment

05:36.280 --> 05:37.648
any time you wanted?

05:37.681 --> 05:39.250
It can do all that?

05:39.283 --> 05:40.884
Reverie is a place

05:40.917 --> 05:43.754
where the impossible becomes possible.

05:43.787 --> 05:46.924
You're put inside a waking
dream of your own design.

05:46.956 --> 05:50.415
You can go anywhere you want,
change your appearance,

05:50.652 --> 05:53.337
and even bring loved ones
back from the dead.

05:53.376 --> 05:54.438
How?

05:54.479 --> 05:57.234
They use what's called a
"social media footprint."

05:57.266 --> 05:59.941
A person's pictures, videos...

06:00.103 --> 06:01.597
their posts.

06:01.739 --> 06:04.159
You feed them into the program,

06:04.307 --> 06:07.152
and you can resurrect them in Reverie.

06:07.903 --> 06:10.074
That's like a field trip to heaven.

06:10.114 --> 06:12.950
Problem is, some of our users
are so addicted

06:13.002 --> 06:15.018
to the fantastic worlds they've created

06:15.043 --> 06:18.379
that their subconscious minds
have severed ties with reality.

06:18.422 --> 06:20.791
Their bodies have gone into a coma.

06:20.823 --> 06:23.326
For lack of a better word,
they're trapped.

06:23.360 --> 06:25.362
I'm still not understanding.

06:25.396 --> 06:27.698
What exactly is it
that you want me to do?

06:27.730 --> 06:29.766
I want you to go inside Reverie

06:29.799 --> 06:31.302
and bring them back.

06:33.836 --> 06:35.905
<i>How would you like to proceed?</i>

06:35.939 --> 06:37.775
She needs time to think about it.

06:37.807 --> 06:39.709
<i>Charlie, we don't have time.</i>

06:39.742 --> 06:41.978
Monica, she's our best option.

06:42.011 --> 06:45.182
Well, you've got her résumé.
See for yourself.

06:47.985 --> 06:50.388
<i>Master's of Psychology from Stanford.</i>

06:53.057 --> 06:56.694
<i>Specialized counterterrorism
training with the FBI.</i>

06:56.727 --> 06:58.328
<i>There have to be others.</i>

06:58.362 --> 07:00.698
<i>The best negotiators make you feel like</i>

07:00.730 --> 07:03.293
<i>you've known them your whole life.</i>

07:03.726 --> 07:05.970
<i>They're attuned to every response:</i>

07:06.002 --> 07:08.271
<i>every little gesture of the hand,</i>

07:08.304 --> 07:10.174
<i>slight change in tone of voice.</i>

07:10.206 --> 07:12.308
<i>She had all that.</i>

07:12.341 --> 07:15.311
<i>She worked miracles
for complete strangers.</i>

07:18.215 --> 07:19.950
<i>Unfortunately, she couldn't do it</i>

07:19.982 --> 07:22.336
<i>for the people she loved the most.</i>

07:29.359 --> 07:32.700
Whoa, whoa, whoa. Ray, Ray.

07:32.795 --> 07:34.898
Okay, so just, uh...
Just back up a second.

07:34.932 --> 07:36.734
You know? Tell me how all of this

07:36.766 --> 07:38.101
got started.

07:38.134 --> 07:40.198
- I found a text.
- Okay, a text, good.

07:40.237 --> 07:41.706
- What text?
- On Jamie's phone.

07:41.739 --> 07:43.140
A text on Jamie's phone. Great.

07:43.172 --> 07:44.144
What did it say?

07:44.169 --> 07:46.476
That she's taking Brynn
to your parents' place.

07:46.509 --> 07:49.412
- She's gonna leave me.
- Okay, wait, wait.

07:49.446 --> 07:51.948
Ray, listen.

07:51.982 --> 07:53.451
I'm sure it wasn't permanent, all right?

07:53.484 --> 07:54.785
I-I-I...

07:54.818 --> 07:57.188
Maybe she just wanted
to give you guys some space.

07:57.220 --> 07:58.618
I know my sister.

07:58.665 --> 08:00.191
I know how much she loves you.

08:00.223 --> 08:01.925
Not anymore.

08:01.958 --> 08:04.461
No, of course she does.

08:04.494 --> 08:06.362
Remember when you used to

08:06.396 --> 08:08.331
come to our house and you would

08:08.371 --> 08:09.741
pick her up for dates

08:09.766 --> 08:11.134
and you would drive around in that car.

08:11.159 --> 08:12.427
God, what was it? It was the, um...

08:12.468 --> 08:14.204
The... the... The black one...

08:14.237 --> 08:16.840
- The Camaro?
- The Camaro, exactly.

08:16.894 --> 08:19.176
Whatever happened to that car, anyway?

08:19.208 --> 08:20.477
I sold it...

08:22.637 --> 08:24.348
To, uh, buy Jamie's ring.

08:29.252 --> 08:30.453
I'm sorry, baby.

08:30.487 --> 08:32.155
Daddy didn't mean to scare you.

08:32.188 --> 08:33.789
I didn't mean to scare you.
Everything's going to be...

08:40.087 --> 08:42.991
- Did you call the police?
- Mara...

08:43.015 --> 08:44.936
No! No, no.

08:44.961 --> 08:46.912
- I-I... No, no, no.
- Oh, I told you

08:46.951 --> 08:48.587
- not to call the police!
- They're going to go away.

08:48.642 --> 08:50.908
No, I didn't!
I'm gonna make them go away.

08:50.937 --> 08:52.525
Please, please...

08:52.572 --> 08:55.513
Ray! Ray! Ray! Ray!

